# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: consumer-organization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:consumer-organization/actor-analysis] Instead of parties, we speak of actors which comprise both individuals and groups like organizations, administrative authorities or consumer organisations.
[src:consumer-organization/actor-analysis] All these actors can change an existing situation by their priorities or value systems.
[src:consumer-organization/actor-analysis] There have been many changes of environmental behaviour that can be described via actor analysis.
[src:consumer-organization/actor-analysis] For example, all cars are now equipped with catalytic converters.
[src:consumer-organization/actor-analysis] Environmental organisations, governments, companies, legislators, and customers have all been actors in this process.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] An **advertising campaign** or **marketing campaign** is a series of advertisement messages that share a single idea and theme which make up an integrated marketing communication (IMC).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] An IMC is a platform in which a group of people can group their ideas, beliefs, and concepts into one large media base.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Advertising campaigns utilize diverse media channels over a particular time frame and target identified audiences.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The campaign theme is the central message that will be received in the promotional activities and is the prime focus of the advertising campaign, as it sets the motif for the series of individual advertisements and other marketing communications that will be used.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The campaign themes are usually produced with the objective of being used for a significant period but many of them are temporal due to factors like being not effective or market conditions, competition and marketing mix.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Advertising campaigns are built to accomplish a particular objective or a set of objectives.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Such objectives usually include establishing a brand, raising brand awareness, and aggrandizing the rate of conversions/sales.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The rate of success or failure in accomplishing these goals is reckoned via effectiveness measures.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] There are 5 key points that an advertising campaign must consider to ensure an effective campaign.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] These points are, integrated marketing communications, media channels, positioning, the communications process diagram and touch points.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Integrated marketing communication (IMC) is a conceptual approach used by the majority of organizations to develop a strategic plan on how they are going to broadcast their marketing and advertising campaigns.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Recently there has been a shift in the way marketers and advertisers interact with their consumers and now see it as a conversation between marketing/advertising teams and consumers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] IMC has emerged as a key strategy for organizations to manage customer experiences in the digital age, since organizations can communicate with people in more ways than those typically thought of as media.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The more traditional advertising practices such as newspapers, billboards, and magazines are still used but fail to have the same effect now as they did in previous years.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Current research shows that no other form of commercial communication shares the same essential elements as the mobile forms, making it unique in its advertising impact.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The importance of the IMC is to make the marketing process seamless for both the brand and the consumer.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] IMC attempts to meld all aspects of marketing into one cohesive piece.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This includes sales promotion, advertising, public relations, direct marketing, and social media.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The entire point of IMC is to have all of these aspects of marketing work together as a unified force.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This can be done through methods, channels, and activities all while using a media platform.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The end goal of IMC is to get the brand's message across to consumers in the most convenient way possible.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The advantage of using IMC is that it can communicate the same message through several channels to create brand awareness.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] IMC is the most cost-effective solution when compared to mass media advertising to interact with target consumers on a personal level.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] IMC also benefits small businesses, as they are able to submerge their consumers with communication of various kinds in a way that pushes them through the research and buying stages creating a relationship and dialogue with their new customer.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] In-store sales promotions are tactics such as '30% off' sales or offering loyalty cards to consumers to build a relationship.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Television and radio advertisements are also a form of advertising strategy derived from IMC.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] All of the components of IMC play an important role and a company may or may not choose to implement any of the integration strategies.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Media channels, also known as, marketing communications channels, are used to create a connection with the target consumer and influence the behavior.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Traditional methods of communication with the consumer include newspapers, magazines, radio, television, billboards, telephone, post, and door to door sales.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] These are just a few of the historically traditional methods.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Along with traditional media channels, there are new and emerging media channels.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Social media has begun to play a significant role in the way media and marketing combine to reach a consumer base.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Social media can reach a wider audience.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Depending on age group and demographic, social media can influence a company's overall image.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Using social media as a marketing tool has become a widely popular branding method.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] A brand can create an entire social media presence based around its specific target.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] With advancements in digital communications channels, marketing communications allow for the possibility of two-way communications where an immediate consumer response can be elicited.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Digital communications tools include: websites, blogs, social media, email, mobile, and search engines as a few examples.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] It is important for an advertising campaign to carefully select channels based on where their target consumer spends time to ensure market and advertising efforts are maximized.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Marketing professionals should also consider the cost of reaching its target audience and the time (i.e. advertising during the holiday season tends to be more expensive).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] In the rapidly changing marketing and advertising environment, exposure to certain consumer groups and target audiences through traditional media channels has blurred.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] These traditional media channels are defined as print, broadcast, out-of-home and direct mail.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The introduction of various new modern-day media channels has altered their traditional advantages and disadvantages.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] It is imperative to the effectiveness of the Integrated Marketing Communication (IMC) strategy that exposure to certain demographics, consumer groups and target audiences is anticipated to provide clarity, consistency, and maximum communications impact.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Print media is mainly defined as newspapers and magazines.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] With the transition in around 2006 – 2016 to digital information on phones, computers and tablets, the main demographic that is still exposed to traditional print media is older.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] It is also estimated that there will be a reduction of print material in the coming years, as print media moves online.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Advertisers need to consider this; in some cases, they could use this to their advantage.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The advantages of newspaper advertising are that it is low cost, timely, the reader controls exposure, and it provides moderate coverage to the older generations in western society.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Disadvantages are the aging demographic, short life, clutter and that it attracts less attention.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Magazines are similar in some cases, but as they are a niche product they increase segmentation potential; they also have high information content and longevity.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Disadvantages are that they are visual only, they lack flexibility and a long lead time for advertisement placement.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Traditional broadcast media's primary platforms are television and radio.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] These are still relatively prominent in modern-day society, but with the emergence of online content such as YouTube and Instagram, it would be difficult to anticipate where the market is headed in the next decade.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Television's advantages are that it has mass coverage, high reach, quality reputation, low post per exposure and impacts human senses.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Disadvantages would be that it has low selectivity, short message life and high production costs.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Alternatively, radio offers flexibility, high frequency and low advertising and production costs.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Disadvantages to radio are that its audio only, low attention-getting and short message.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Out of Home (OOH) marketing is a broad concept that has expanded beyond large, static billboards on motorways.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Current and innovative OOH approaches include street furniture, aerial blimps and digital OOH.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] As the world changes, new ways emerges to revitalize this media channel.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Its potential advantages are accessibility and reach, geographic flexibility and relatively low cost.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Disadvantages to OOH media are that it has a short life, is difficult to measure/control and can convey a poor brand image.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Direct mail consists of messages sent directly to consumers through the mail delivery service.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] It is one of the more "dated" media channels.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] In the modern day it has few advantages, except that it can be highly selective, and has high information content.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Disadvantages are that it promotes a poor brand image ("junk mail") and has a high cost-to-contact ratio.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] When an organisation begins to construct their advertising campaign they need to research each and every aspect of their target market and target consumers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The target consumers (or "potential customers") are the people who are most likely to buy from an organisation.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] They can be categorized by several key characteristics: mainly gender, age, occupation, marital status, geographical location, behavioral, level of income and education.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This process is called segmenting customers on the basis of demographics.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Defining the target market helps businesses and individuals design a marketing campaign.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This in turn helps businesses and individuals avoid waste and get their advertisements to likely customers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] While attempting to find the correct target market it is important to focus on specific groups of individuals that will benefit.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] By marketing to specific groups of individuals that specifically relate to the product, businesses and individuals will more quickly and efficiently find those who will purchase the product.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Businesses and individuals that monitor their existing data (customer and sales data) will find it easier to define their target market, and surveying existing customers will assist in finding more customers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Avoiding inefficiencies when finding a target market is equally as important.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Wasting time and money advertising to a large group of potential customers is inefficient if only a handful become customers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] A focused plan that reaches a tiny audience can work out well if they're already interested in a product.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] People interested today might not be interested tomorrow, and those not interested in the present time might become interested over time.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Analysing sales data and customer information helps businesses and individuals understand when their target market is increasing or decreasing.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] There are many advantages that are associated with finding a target market.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] One advantage is the "ability to offer the right product" (Suttle.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] 2016) through knowing the age and needs of the customer willing to purchase the item.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Another advantage of target marketing assists businesses in understanding what price the customer will pay for the products or service.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Businesses are also more efficient and effective at advertising their product, because they "reach the right consumers with messages that are more applicable" (Suttle.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] However, there are several disadvantages that can be associated with target marketing.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Firstly, finding a target market is expensive.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Often businesses conduct primary research to find whom their target market is, which usually involves hiring a research agency, which can cost "tens of thousands of dollars" (Suttle, R.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Finding one's target market is also time-consuming, as it often "requires a considerable amount of time to identify a target audience" (Suttle, R.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Also focusing on finding a target market can make one overlook other customers that may be in a product.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Businesses or individuals may find that their 'average customer' might not include those that fall just outside of the average customers "demographics" (Suttle, R.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] 2016), which will limit the sale of their products.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The last disadvantage to note is the ethical ramifications that are associated with target marketing.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] An example of this would be a "beer company that may target less educated, poorer people with larger-sized bottles" (Suttle, R.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] In advertising various brands compete to the most important brand to the consumer.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Everyday consumers view advertising and rank particular brands compared to their competitors.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Individuals rank these specific brands in an order of what is most important to them.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] For example, a person may compare brands of cars based on how sporty they think they look, affordability, practicality and classiness.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Positioning is an important marketing concept that businesses implement to market their products or services.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The positioning concept focuses on creating an image that will best attract the intended audience.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Businesses that implement the positioning concept focus on promotion, price, placement and product.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] When the positioning concept is effective and productive it elevates the marketing efforts made by a business, and assists the buyer in purchasing the product.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The positioning process is imperative in marketing because of the specific level of consumer-based recognition is involved.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] A company must create a trademark brand for themselves in order to be recognizable by a broad range of consumers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] For example, a fast food restaurant positions itself as fast, cheap, and delicious.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] They are playing upon their strengths and most visible characteristics.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] On the other hand, a luxury car brand will position its brand as a stylish and expensive platform because they want to target a specific brand very different from the fast food brand.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] For the positioning concept to be effective one must focus on the concepts of promotion, price, place and product.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] There are three basic objectives of promotion, which include: presenting product information to targeted business customers and consumers, increase demand among the target market, and differentiating a product and creating a brand identity.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Tools that can be used to achieve these objectives are advertising, public relations, personal selling, direct marketing, and sales promotion.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Price of an object is crucial in the concept of positioning.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Adjusting or decreasing the product price has a profound impact on the sales of the product, and should complement the other parts of the positioning concept.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The price needs to ensure survival, increase profit, generate survival, gain market shares, and establish an appropriate image.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Promoting a product is essential in the positioning concept.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] It is the process marketers use to communicate their products' attributes to the intended target market.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] In order for products to be successful businesses must focus on the customer needs, competitive pressures, available communication channels and carefully crafted key messages.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Product Positioning presents several advantages in the advertising campaign, and to the businesses/ individuals that implement it.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Positioning connects with superior aspects of a product and matches "them with consumers more effectively than competitors" (Jaideep, S.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Positioning can also help businesses or individuals realise the consumer's expectations of the product/s they are willing to purchase from them.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Positioning a product reinforces the companies name, product and brand.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] It also makes the brand popular and strengthens customer loyalty.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Product benefits to customers are better advertised through positioning the product, which results in more interest and attention of consumers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This also attracts different types of consumers as products posse's different benefits that attract different groups of consumers, for example: a shoe that is advertised for playing sports, going for walks, hiking and casual wear will attract different groups of consumers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Another advantage of positioning is the competitive strength it gives to businesses/ individuals and their products, introducing new products successfully to the market and communicating new and varied features that are added to a product later on.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The Communication of processes diagram refers to the order of operation an advertising campaign pieces together the flow of communication between a given organisation and the consumer.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The diagram usually flows left to right (unless shown in a circular array) starting with the source.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] An advertising campaign uses the communication process diagram to ensure all the appropriate steps of communication are being taken in order.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The source is the person or organisation that has a message they want to share with potential consumers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] An example of this is Vodafone wanting to tell their consumers and new consumers of a new monthly plan.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The diagram then moves on to encoding which consists of the organisation putting messages, thoughts and ideas into a symbolic form that be interpreted by the target consumer using symbols or words.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The third stage in the diagram is channel message.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This occurs when the information or meaning the source wants to convoy, is put into a form to easily be transmitted to the targeted audience.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This also includes the method that communication gets from the source to the receiver.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Examples of this is Vodafone advertising on TV, bus stops and university campuses as students may be the intended consumer for the new plan.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Decoding is the processes that the viewer interprets the message that the source sent.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Obviously it is up to the source to ensure that the message encoded well enough so that it is received as intended.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The receiver is also known as the viewer or potential consumer.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This is the person who interprets the source message through channeling whether they are the intended target audience or not.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Every day we interpret different advertisements even if we are not the target audience for that advertisement.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] In between these steps there are external factors acting as distractions, these factors are called noise.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Noise distorts the way the message gets to the intended target audience.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] These distractions are from all other forms of advertising and communication from every other person or organisation.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Examples of noise are State of mind, unfamiliar language, unclear message, Values, Attitudes, Perceptions, Culture and Knowledge of similar products or services to name a few forms of noise.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Finally there is the response or feedback.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This is the receiver's reaction to the communication of message and the way they understood it.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Feedback relates to the way sales react as well as the interest or questions that arise in relation to the message put out.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] When considering touch points in an advertising campaign a brand looks for Multisensory touch points.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] These touch points help the brand to develop a point of contact between themselves and the consumer.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Modern day advancements in various forms of technology have made it easier for consumers to engage with brands in numerous ways.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The most successful touch points are those that create value in the consumer and brands relationship.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Common examples of touch points include social media links, QR codes, person handing out flyers about a particular brand, billboards, web sites and various other methods that connect the brand and consumer.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The most effective touch points, as found in Effie Award- winning campaigns, are: interactive (91%), followed by TV (63%), print (52%) and consumer involvement (51%).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Multi sensory touch points are subconscious yet helps use to recognise brands through characteristic identified through human sensors.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] These characteristics could be shape, colour, textures, sounds, smell or tastes associated with a given brand.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] It is important for an advertising campaign to consider sensory cues into their campaign as market places continue to become increasingly competitive and crowded.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Anyone of the given sensory characteristics may remind a person of the brand they best associate with.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] A prime example of this is Red Bull who use the colour, shapes and size of their cans to best relate their product to success and winning.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] A taller can looks like the 1st place podium when placed next to competitors, the design looks like the finish flag in racing representing winning.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The opportunity for an advertising campaign to succeed is significantly increased with the use of multi sensory touch points used as a point of difference between brands.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla marketing is an advertising strategy which increases brand exposure through the use of unconventional campaigns which initiate social discussion and "buzz".
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This can often be achieved with lower budgets than conventional advertising methods, allowing small and medium-sized businesses the chance to compete against larger competitors.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Through unconventional methods, inventiveness and creativity, guerrilla marketing leaves the receiver with a long lasting impression of the brand as most guerrilla marketing campaigns target the receivers at a personal level, taking them by surprise and may incorporate an element of shock.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla marketing is typically executed exclusively in public places, including streets, parks, shopping centres etc., to ensure maximum audience resulting in further discussion on social media.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla marketing is the term used for several types of marketing categories including street marketing, ambient marketing, presence marketing, alternative marketing, experimental marketing, grassroots marketing, flyposting, guerrilla projection advertising, undercover marketing and astroturfing.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Jay Conrad Levinson coined the term *Guerrilla Marketing* with his 1984 book of the same name.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Through the enhancement of technology and common use of internet and mobile phones, marketing communication has become more affordable and guerrilla marketing is on the rise, allowing the spread of newsworthy guerrilla campaigns.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] When establishing a guerrilla marketing strategy, there are seven elements to a clear and logical approach.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Firstly, write a statement that identifies the purpose of the strategy.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Secondly define how the purpose will be achieved concentrating on the key advantages.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Next Levinson (1989) suggests writing a descriptive summary on the target market or consumers.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The fourth element is to establish a statement that itemizes the marketing tools and methods planning to be used in the strategy (for example, radio advertising during 6.30am – 9am on weekday mornings or window displays that are regularly updated).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The fifth step is to create a statement which positions the brand/product/company in the market.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Define the brands characteristics and give it an identity is the sixth element.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Lastly, clearly identify a budget which will be put solely towards marketing going forward.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] For a successful overall guerrilla marketing campaign, combine the above steps with seven winning actions.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Levinson suggests guerrilla marketing tactics were initiated to enable small businesses with limited financial resources to gain an upper hand on the corporate giants who had unlimited budgets and resources at their disposal.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Large companies cottoned on to the success of guerrilla marketing and have had hundreds of effective attention grabbing campaigns using the strategies originally designed for smaller businesses with minimal marketing budgets.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Non-traditional, unconventional and shocking campaigns are highly successful in obtaining media coverage and therefore brand awareness, albeit good or bad media attention.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] However, like most marketing strategies a bad campaign can backfire and damage profits and sales.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Undercover marketing and astroturfing are two type of guerrilla marketing that are deemed as risky and can be detrimental to the company.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] "Advertising can be dated back to 4000 BC where Egyptians used papyrus to make sales messages and wall posters.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Traditional advertising and marketing slowly developed over the centuries but never bloomed until early 1900s" ("What Is Guerrilla Marketing?", 2010).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla marketing are relatively simple, use tactics to advertise on a very small budget.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] It is to make a campaign that is "shocking, funny, unique, outrageous, clever and creative that people can't stop talking about it" (Uk essays, 2016).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla marketing is different when compared to traditional marketing tactics (Staff, 2016).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] "Guerrilla marketing means going after conventional goals of profits, sales and growth but doing it by using unconventional means, such as expanding offerings during gloomy economic days to inspire customers to increase the size of each purchase" (Staff, 2016).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla marketing also suggests that rather than investing money, it is better to "invest time, energy, imagination and knowledge" (Staff, 2016) instead.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla marketing puts profit as their main priority not sales as their main focal point, this is done to urge the growth of geometrically by enlarging the size of each transactions.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] This all done through one of the most powerful marketing weapons around, the telephone.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Research shows that it will always increases profits and sales.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The term "guerrilla first appeared during the war of independence in Spain and Portugal at the beginning of the 19th century it can be translated as battle" (Uk essays, 2016).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Even thou guerrilla marketing was aimed for small business; this did not stop bigger business from adopting the same ideology.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] "Larger business has been using unconventional marketing to complement their advertising campaigns, even then some marketers argue that when bigger business utilize guerrilla marketing tactics, it isn't true guerrilla" ("What Is Guerrilla Marketing?", 2010).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The reason being that larger companies have bigger budgets and usually their brands well established.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] In some cases, it is far riskier for a larger business to do guerrilla marketing tactics.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Which can cause problem when their stunts become a flop when compared to smaller business, as they do not run as much risk, as most people will just write it off as another failed stunt.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Small business use social media as a form of marketing.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] "Collecting billions of people around the world through a series of status updates, tweets, and other rich media" ("Guerrilla Marketing Strategies for Small Businesses", 2013).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Social media is a powerful tool in the world of business.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla marketing strategies and tactics are a great and cost effective way to generate" awareness for business, products and services.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] To maximize full potential of marketing efforts, it's to blend them with a powerful and robust online marking strategy with a marketing automation software" ("Guerrilla Marketing Strategies for Small Businesses", 2013).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla tactics consist of instruments that have effects on the efforts.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Some instruments are usually there to maximize the surprise effect and some of these instruments mainly cutting advertising costs." Guerrilla marketing is a way of increasing the number of individuals exposed to the advertising with the cost of campaign.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] The instrument of diffusion helps to each a wide audience, which causes none or little cost because consumers (viral marketing) or the media (guerrilla PR) pass on the advertising message" ("Guerrilla Marketing: The Nature of the Concept and Propositions for Further Research", 2016).
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla campaigns usually implement a free ride approach, this means that to cut their costs and increase the number of recipients simultaneously to maximize the low cost effect.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] For example, they will try to benefit from placing advertisements on big events e.g. sporting events.
[src:consumer-organization/advertising-campaign] Guerrilla marketing was regarded to target existing customers rather than new ones, aiming to increase their engagement with a product and/ or brand.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] There are several forms of advocacy, each representing a different approach in a way to initiate changes in the society.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] One of the most popular forms is social justice advocacy.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Cohen, de la Vega, and Watson (2001) state that this definition does not encompass the notions of power relations, people's participation, and a vision of a just society as promoted by social justice advocates.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Symbolic politics: calling upon symbols, actions, or stories that make sense of a situation for an audience that is frequently far away.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Leverage politics: calling upon powerful actors to affect a situation where weaker members of a network are unlikely to have influence.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Accountability politics: efforts to hold powerful actors to their previously stated policies or principles.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] These tactics have been also observed within advocacy organizations outside the USA.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] The four tactics popularly described for advocacy networks are information politics, symbolic politics, leverage politics and accountability politics.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Groups involved in advocacy have increasingly used the Internet and social media to increase the speed, reach and effectiveness of communications and mobilization; research has documented both benefits and new challenges for civic engagement in the digital era.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Effective advocacy increasingly relies on monitoring and evaluation to show whether campaigns produce intended policy changes; this requires theory-of-change statements, measurement of outputs and outcomes, and careful attention to attribution.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Ethical issues include transparency of funding and tactics, privacy concerns in digital organising, and the risk of manipulative messaging.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Advocacy activities may include conducting an exit poll or the filing of an amicus brief.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] People advocate for a large number and variety of topics.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Some of these are clear-cut social issues that are universally agreed to be problematic and worth solving, such as human trafficking.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Others—such as abortion—are much more divisive and inspire strongly held opinions on both sides.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] There may never be a consensus on this latter type of issues, but intense advocacy is likely to remain.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] In the United States, any issue of widespread debate and deeply divided opinion can be referred to as a social issue.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] The Library of Congress has assembled an extensive list of social issues in the United States, ranging from vast ones like abortion to same-sex marriage to smaller ones like hacking and academic cheating.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Topics that appear to involve advancing a certain positive ideal are often known as causes.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] A particular cause may be very expansive in nature — for instance, increasing liberty or fixing a broken political system.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Topics upon which there is universal agreement that they need to be solved include, for example, human trafficking, poverty, water and sanitation as a human right.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] "Social issues" as referred to in the United States also include topics (also known as "causes") intended by their advocates to advance certain ideals (such as equality) include: civil rights, LGBT rights, women's rights, environmentalism, and veganism.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Advocates and advocacy groups represent a wide range of categories and support several issues as listed on worldadvocacy.com.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] The Advocacy Institute, a US-based global organization, is dedicated to strengthening the capacity of political, social, and economic justice advocates to influence and change public policy.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] The phenomenon of globalization draws a special attention to advocacy beyond countries’ borders.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] The core existence of networks such as World Advocacy or the Advocacy Institute demonstrates the increasing importance of transnational advocacy and international advocacy.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Transnational advocacy networks are more likely to emerge around issues where external influence is necessary to ease the communication between internal groups and their own government.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Groups of advocates willing to further their mission also tend to promote networks and to meet with their internal counterparts to exchange ideas.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Transnational advocacy is increasingly playing a role in advocacy for migrants rights, and migrant advocacy organizations have strategically called upon governments and international organizations for leverage.
[src:consumer-organization/advocacy] Transnational advocates spend time with local interest groups in order to better understand their views and wishes.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The **aftermath of World War II** saw the rise of two global superpowers, the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Once allies during World War II, the United States and the Soviet Union became competitors on the world stage and engaged in the Cold War, so called because it never resulted in overt, declared total war between the two powers.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It was instead characterized by espionage, political subversion, and proxy wars.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Western Europe was rebuilt through the American Marshall Plan, whereas Central and Eastern Europe fell under the Soviet sphere of influence and eventually behind an "Iron Curtain." Europe was divided into a U.S.-led Western Bloc and a Soviet-led Eastern Bloc.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Internationally, alliances with the two blocs gradually shifted, with some nations trying to stay out of the Cold War through the Non-Aligned Movement.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Cold War also saw a nuclear arms race between the two superpowers, and part of the reason that the Cold War never became a "hot" war was that the Soviet Union and the United States had nuclear deterrents against each other, leading to a mutually assured destruction standoff.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As a consequence of the war, the Allies created the United Nations, an organization for international cooperation and diplomacy, similar to the League of Nations.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Members of the United Nations agreed to outlaw wars of aggression in an attempt to avoid a third world war.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The devastated great powers of Western Europe formed the European Coal and Steel Community, which later evolved into the European Economic Community and ultimately into the current European Union.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This effort primarily began as an attempt to avoid another war between West Germany and France through economic cooperation and integration, and a common market for important natural resources.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The State of Israel was also established following the disestablishment of the British-ruled Mandatory Palestine and the 1948 Palestine War.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Nations in Sub-Saharan Africa achieved independence in the 1950s to 1970s.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The aftermath of World War II saw the rise of communist influence in East and Southeast Asia.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The People's Republic of China was founded after the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) emerged victorious from the Chinese Civil War in 1949, and the First Indochina War was fought between the Viet Minh government and France after the Japanese retreat.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Korean War led to the division of the Korean Peninsula between the communist North Korea and the Western-aligned South Korea.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the end of the war in Europe, tens of millions of people had been killed and even more were displaced, European economies had collapsed, and much of Europe's industrial infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In response, in 1947 US Secretary of State George C.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Marshall devised the "European Recovery Program," which became known as the Marshall Plan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Under the plan, from 1948 to 1952 the United States government allocated $13 billion (US$140 billion in 2024 dollars) for the reconstruction of affected countries in Western Europe.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By the end of the war, the economy of the United Kingdom was one of severe privation, as a significant portion of its national wealth had been consumed by the war effort.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Until the introduction in 1941 of Lend-Lease aid from the United States, the UK had been spending its assets to purchase American equipment including aircraft and ships—over £437 million (equivalent to some £29 billion in 2024) on aircraft alone.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Lend-Lease came just before its reserves were exhausted.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain had placed 55% of its total labour force into war production.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the spring of 1945, after the final defeat of Germany, the Labour Party withdrew from the wartime coalition government to oust Winston Churchill, forcing a general election.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following a landslide victory, Labour held more than 60% of the seats in the House of Commons and formed a new government on 26 July 1945 under Clement Attlee, who had been Deputy Prime Minister in the coalition government.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Lend-Lease support to Britain on 2 September 1945 dealt a severe blow to the plans of the new government.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It was only with the completion of the Anglo-American loan by the United States to Great Britain on 15 July 1946 that some measure of economic stability was restored.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, the loan was made primarily to support British overseas expenditure in the immediate post-war years and not to implement the Labour government's policies for domestic welfare reforms and the nationalisation of key industries.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Although the loan was agreed on reasonable terms, its conditions included what proved to be damaging fiscal conditions for sterling.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] From 1946 to 1948, the UK introduced bread rationing, which it had never done during the war.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union suffered enormous losses in the war against Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet population decreased by about 27 million during the war; of these, 8.7 million were combatant deaths.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Soviet ex-POWs and civilians repatriated from abroad were suspected of having been Nazi collaborators, and 226,127 of them were sent to forced labour camps after scrutiny by Soviet intelligence, NKVD.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Many ex-POWs and young civilians were also conscripted to serve in the Red Army.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Others worked in labour battalions to rebuild infrastructure destroyed during the war.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Roughly a quarter of the Soviet Union's capital resources were destroyed, and industrial and agricultural output in 1945 fell far short of pre-war levels.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To help rebuild the country, the Soviet government obtained limited credits from Britain and Sweden; it refused assistance offered by the United States under the Marshall Plan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Instead, the Soviet Union coerced Soviet-occupied Central and Eastern Europe to supply machinery and raw materials.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Germany and former Nazi satellites made reparations to the Soviet Union.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The reconstruction programme emphasized heavy industry to the detriment of agriculture and consumer goods.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By 1953, steel production was twice its 1940 level, but the production of many consumer goods and foodstuffs was lower than it had been in the late 1920s.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The immediate post-war period in Europe was dominated by the Soviet Union annexing, or converting into Soviet Socialist Republics, all the countries invaded and annexed by the Red Army driving the Germans out of central and eastern Europe.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] New satellite states were set up by the Soviets in Poland, Bulgaria, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, Romania, Albania, and East Germany; the last of these was created from the Soviet zone of occupation in Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Yugoslavia emerged as an independent Communist state allied but not aligned with the Soviet Union, owing to the independent nature of the military victory of the Partisans of Josip Broz Tito during World War II in Yugoslavia.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Allies established the Far Eastern Commission and Allied Council for Japan to administer their occupation of that country while the establishment Allied Control Council, administered occupied Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the Potsdam Conference agreements, the Soviet Union occupied and subsequently annexed the strategic island of Sakhalin.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the east, the Sudetenland reverted to Czechoslovakia following the European Advisory Commission's decision to delimit German territory to be the territory it held on 31 December 1937.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Close to one-quarter of pre-war (1937) Nazi Germany was *de facto* annexed by the Allies; roughly 10 million Germans were either expelled from this territory or not permitted to return to it if they had fled during the war.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The remainder of Germany was partitioned into four zones of occupation, coordinated by the Allied Control Council.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Saar was detached and put into economic union with France in 1947.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1949, the Federal Republic of Germany was created out of the Western zones.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet zone became the German Democratic Republic.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Germany paid reparations to the United Kingdom, France, and the Soviet Union, mainly in the form of dismantled factories, forced labour, and coal.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The German standard of living was to be reduced to its 1932 level.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Beginning immediately after the German surrender and continuing for the next two years, the U.S. and Britain pursued an "intellectual reparations" programme to harvest all technological and scientific know-how as well as all patents in Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The value of these amounted to around $10 billion (US$120 billion in 2024 dollars).
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In accordance with the Paris Peace Treaties, 1947, reparations were also assessed from the countries of Italy, Romania, Hungary, Bulgaria, and Finland.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] US policy in post-war Germany from April 1945 until July 1947 had been that no help should be given to the Germans in rebuilding their nation, save for the minimum required to mitigate starvation.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Allies' immediate post-war "industrial disarmament" plan for Germany had been to destroy Germany's capability to wage war by complete or partial de-industrialization.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The first industrial plan for Germany signed in 1946, required the destruction of 1,500 manufacturing plants to lower German heavy industry output to roughly 50% of its 1938 level.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The dismantling of the West German industry ended in 1951.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By 1950, equipment had been removed from 706 manufacturing plants, and steel production capacity had been reduced by 6.7 million tons.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Joint Chiefs of Staff and Generals Lucius D.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Marshall, the Truman administration accepted that economic recovery in Europe could not go forward without the reconstruction of the German industrial base on which it had previously been dependent.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] From 1948 onward West Germany also became a minor beneficiary of the Marshall Plan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Volunteer organizations had initially been forbidden to send food, but in early 1946 the Council of Relief Agencies Licensed to Operate in Germany was founded.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The prohibition against sending CARE Packages to individuals in Germany was rescinded on 5 June 1946.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the German surrender, the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) was prohibited from providing aid such as food or visiting POW camps for Germans inside Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, after making approaches to the Allies in the autumn of 1945 it was allowed to investigate the camps in the United Kingdom and French occupation zones of Germany, as well as to provide relief to the prisoners held there.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 4 February 1946, the ICRC was also permitted to visit and assist prisoners in the U.S. occupation zone of Germany, although only with very small quantities of food.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The ICRC petitioned successfully for improvements to be made in the living conditions of German POWs.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The German people as a whole, especially its youth, were traumatized psychologically by the previous decade of Nazi rule, with major cities and infrastructure destroyed by Allied bombardments.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the end of the war, major cities were devastated, food shortages ensued, and a wave of denazification occurred throughout occupied Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As France was liberated from German occupation, an *épuration* (purge) of real and suspected Nazi collaborators began.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] At first, this was undertaken in an extralegal manner by the French Resistance (called the *épuration sauvage*, "wild purge").
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] French women who had had romantic liaisons with German soldiers were publicly humiliated and had their heads shaved.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] There was also a wave of summary executions estimated to have killed about 10,000 people.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] When the Provisional Government of the French Republic established control, the *Épuration légale* ("legal purge") began.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] There were no international war crimes trials for French collaborators, who were tried in the domestic courts.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Approximately 300,000 cases were investigated; 120,000 people were given various sentences including 6,763 death sentences (of which only 791 were carried out).
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Most convicts were given amnesty a few years later.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The aftermath of World War II left Italy with an anger against the monarchy for its endorsement of the Fascist regime for the previous twenty years.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] These frustrations contributed to a revival of the Italian republican movement.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the 1946 Italian constitutional referendum, held on 2 June, a day celebrated since as *Festa della Repubblica*, the Italian monarchy was abolished, having been associated with the deprivations of the war and the Fascist rule, especially in the North, and Italy became a republic.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This was the first time that Italian women voted at the national level, and the second time overall considering the local elections that were held a few months earlier in some cities.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] King Victor Emmanuel III's son, King Umberto II, was forced to abdicate and exiled.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Republican Constitution was approved on 1 January 1948, resulting from the work of a Constituent Assembly formed by the representatives of all the anti-fascist forces that contributed to the defeat of Nazi and Fascist forces during the liberation of Italy.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The 1947 Treaty of Peace compelled Italy to pay $360 million (US dollars at 1938 prices) in war reparations: $125 million to Yugoslavia, $105 million to Greece, $100 million to the Soviet Union, $25 million to Ethiopia, and $5 million to Albania.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1954 the Free Territory of Trieste, an independent territory between northern Italy and Yugoslavia under direct responsibility of the UN Security Council, was divided between the two states, Italy and Yugoslavia.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Italian border that applies today has existed since 1975, when Trieste was formally re-annexed to Italy after the Treaty of Osimo.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1950 Italian Somaliland was made a United Nations Trust Territory under Italian administration until 1 July 1960.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Federal State of Austria had been annexed by Germany in 1938 (Anschluss, this union was banned by the Treaty of Versailles).
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Austria (called Ostmark by the Germans) was separated from Germany and divided into four zones of occupation.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] With the Austrian State Treaty, these zones reunited in 1955 to become the Republic of Austria.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the war, the Allies rescinded the Empire of Japan's pre-war annexations such as Manchuria, and Korea became militarily occupied by the United States in the south and by the Soviet Union in the north.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Philippines and Guam were returned to the United States.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Burma, Malaya, and Singapore were returned to Britain and Indochina back to France.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Dutch East Indies was to be handed back to the Dutch but was resisted leading to the Indonesian war for independence.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Roosevelt had secretly traded the Japanese Kurils and south Sakhalin to the Soviet Union in return for Soviet entry into the war with Japan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union annexed the Kuril Islands, provoking the Kuril Islands dispute, which is ongoing, as Russia continues to occupy the islands.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Hundreds of thousands of Japanese were forced to relocate to the Japanese main islands.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Okinawa became a main U.S. staging point.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The U.S. covered large areas of it with military bases and continued to occupy it until 1972, years after the end of the occupation of the main islands.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To skirt the Geneva Convention, the Allies classified many Japanese soldiers as Japanese Surrendered Personnel (JSP) instead of POWs and used them as forced labour until 1947.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United Kingdom, France, and the Netherlands used JSP to support their military operations in the region after World War II.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] General Douglas MacArthur established the International Military Tribunal for the Far East.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Allies collected reparations from Japan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To further remove Japan as a potential future military threat, the Far Eastern Commission decided to de-industrialize Japan, to reduce the Japanese standard of living to what prevailed between 1930 and 1934.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the end, the de-industrialisation programme in Japan was implemented to a lesser degree than the one in Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Japan received emergency aid from GARIOA, as did Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In early 1946, the Licensed Agencies for Relief in Asia were formed and permitted to supply Japanese with food and clothes.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In April 1948 the Johnston Committee Report recommended that the economy of Japan should be reconstructed due to the high cost to US taxpayers of continuous emergency aid.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Survivors of the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, known as *hibakusha* (被爆者), were ostracized by Japanese society.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Japan provided no special assistance to these people until 1952.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By the 65th anniversary of the bombings, total casualties from the initial attack and later deaths reached about 270,000 in Hiroshima and 150,000 in Nagasaki.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] About 230,000 hibakusha were still alive as of 2010, and about 2,200 were suffering from radiation-caused illnesses as of 2007.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the Winter War of 1939–1940, the Soviet Union invaded neutral Finland and annexed some of its territory.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] From 1941 until 1944, Finland aligned itself with Nazi Germany in a failed effort to regain lost territories from the Soviets.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Finland retained its independence following the war but remained subject to Soviet-imposed constraints in its domestic affairs.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1940 the Soviet Union invaded and annexed the neutral Baltic states, Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In June 1941, the Soviet governments of the Baltic states carried out mass deportations of "enemies of the people"; as a result, many treated the invading Nazis as liberators when they invaded only a week later.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Atlantic Charter promised self-determination to people deprived of it during the war.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The British Prime Minister, Winston Churchill, argued for a weaker interpretation of the Charter to permit the Soviet Union to continue to control the Baltic states.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In March 1944 the US accepted Churchill's view that the Atlantic Charter did not apply to the Baltic states.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] With the return of Soviet troops at the end of the war, the Forest Brothers mounted a guerrilla war.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] An estimated 1 million military and civilian Filipinos were killed from all causes; of these 131,028 were listed as killed in 72 war crime events.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] According to a United States analysis released years after the war, U.S. casualties were 10,380 dead and 36,550 wounded; Japanese dead were 255,795.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As a result of the new borders drawn by the victorious nations, large populations suddenly found themselves in hostile territory.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union took over areas formerly controlled by Germany, Finland, Poland and Japan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Poland lost the Kresy region (about half of its pre-war territory) and received most of Germany east of the Oder–Neisse line, including the industrial regions of Silesia.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The German state of the Saar was temporarily a protectorate of France but later returned to German administration.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As set forth at Potsdam, approximately 12 million people were expelled from Germany, including 7 million from Germany proper, and three million from the Sudetenland.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] During the war, the United States government interned approximately 110,000 Japanese Americans and Japanese who lived along the Pacific coast of the United States in the wake of Imperial Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Canada interned approximately 22,000 Japanese Canadians, 14,000 of whom were born in Canada.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] After the war, some internees chose to return to Japan, while most remained in North America.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union expelled at least 2 million Poles from the east of the new border approximating the Curzon Line.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This estimate is uncertain as neither the Polish Communist government nor the Soviet government kept track of the number of expelled people.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The number of Polish citizens inhabiting Polish borderlands (Kresy region) was about 13 million before World War II broke out according to official Polish statistics.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Polish citizens killed in the war that originated from the Polish borderlands territory (killed by either the German Nazi regime or the Soviet regime, or expelled to distant parts of Siberia) were accounted as Russian, Ukrainian, or Belarusian casualties of war in official Soviet historiography.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This fact imposes additional difficulties in making the correct estimation of the number of Polish citizens forcibly transferred after the war.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The border change also reversed the results of the 1919–1920 Polish–Soviet War.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Former Polish cities such as Lwów came under the control of the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Additionally, the Soviet Union transferred more than two million people within their borders; these included Germans, Finns, Crimean Tatars and Chechens.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As Soviet troops marched across the Balkans, they committed rapes and robberies in Romania, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, and Yugoslavia.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The population of Bulgaria was largely spared of this treatment, possibly due to a sense of ethnic kinship or to the leadership of Marshal Fyodor Tolbukhin.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The population of Germany was treated significantly worse.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Rape and murder of German civilians was as bad as, and sometimes worse than, Nazi propaganda had anticipated.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Political officers encouraged Soviet troops to seek revenge and terrorise the German population.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On "the basis of *Hochrechnungen* (projections or estimations), [...] 1.9 million German women altogether were raped at the end of the war by Red Army soldiers." About one-third of all German women in Berlin were raped by Soviet forces, and a substantial minority were raped multiple times.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Berlin, contemporary hospital records indicate between 95,000 and 130,000 women were raped by Soviet troops.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] About 10,000 of these women died, mostly by suicide.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Over 4.5 million Germans fled towards the West.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviets initially had no rules against their troops "fraternising" with German women, but by 1947 they started to isolate their troops from the German population in an attempt to stop rape and robbery by the troops.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Not all Soviet soldiers participated in these activities.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Foreign reports of Soviet brutality were denounced as false.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Rape, robbery, and murder were blamed on German bandits impersonating Soviet soldiers.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Some justified Soviet brutality towards German civilians based on previous brutality of German troops toward Russian civilians.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Until the reunification of Germany, East German histories virtually ignored the actions of Soviet troops, and Russian histories still tend to do so.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Reports of mass rapes by Soviet troops were often dismissed as anti-Communist propaganda or the normal byproduct of war.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Rapes also occurred under other Allied forces in Europe, though the majority were committed by Soviet troops.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In a letter to the editor of *Time* published in September 1945, a U.S.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Lilly assumed that only 5% of rapes by American soldiers were reported, making 17,000 GI rapes a possibility, while analysts estimate that 50% of (ordinary peacetime) rapes are reported.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Supporting Lilly's lower figure is the "crucial difference" that for World War II military rapes "it was the commanding officer, not the victim, who brought charges." According to German historian Miriam Gebhardt, as many as 190,000 women were raped by U.S. soldiers in Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] German soldiers left many war children behind in nations such as France and Denmark, which were occupied for an extended period.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] After the war, the children and their mothers often suffered recriminations.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Norway, the "Tyskerunger" (German-kids) suffered greatly.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] During the Italian campaign, the Goumiers, French Moroccan colonial troops attached to the French Expeditionary Forces, have been accused of committing rape and murder against the Italian peasant communities, mostly targeting civilian women and girls, as well as a few men and boys.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Italy the victims of these acts were described as *Marocchinate* meaning literally "Moroccaned" (or people who have been subjected to acts committed by Moroccans).
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] According to Italian victims associations, a total of more than 7,000 civilians, including children, were raped by Goumiers.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the first few weeks of the American military occupation of Japan, rape and other violent crime was widespread in naval ports like Yokohama and Yokosuka but declined shortly afterward.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] There were 1,336 reported rapes during the first 10 days of the occupation of Kanagawa prefecture.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Historian Toshiyuki Tanaka relates that in Yokohama, the capital of the prefecture, there were 119 known rapes in September 1945.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Historians Eiji Takemae and Robert Ricketts state that, "When U.S. paratroopers landed in Sapporo, an orgy of looting, sexual violence, and drunken brawling ensued.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Gang rapes and other sex atrocities were not infrequent" and some of the rape victims committed suicide.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Eighth Army, recorded that in the one instance when the Japanese formed a self-help vigilante guard to protect women from off-duty GIs, the Eighth Army ordered armored vehicles in the battle array into the streets and arrested the leaders, and the leaders received long prison terms.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Rape committed by U.S. soldiers occupying Okinawa was also a notable phenomenon.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] According to Toshiyuki Tanaka, 76 cases of rape or rape-murder were reported during the first five years of the American occupation of Okinawa.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, he claims this is probably not the true figure, as most cases were unreported.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] During World War II, the Japanese military established brothels filled with "comfort women," a euphemism for the 200,000 girls and women who were forced into sexual slavery for Japanese soldiers.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Confucian nations like Korea and China, where premarital sex is considered shameful, the subject of the "comfort women" was ignored for decades after 1945 as the victims were considered pariahs.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Dutch comfort women brought a successful case before the Batavia Military Tribunal in 1948.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Many allied leaders felt that war between the United States and the Soviet Union was likely.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 19 May 1945, the United States Under-Secretary of State Joseph Grew went so far as to say that it was inevitable.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 5 March 1946, in his "Sinews of Peace" (Iron Curtain) speech at Westminster College in Fulton, Missouri, Winston Churchill said "a shadow" had fallen over Europe.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] He described Stalin as having dropped an "Iron Curtain" between East and West.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Stalin responded by charging that co-existence between communist countries and the West was impossible.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In mid-1948 the Soviet Union imposed a blockade on the Western zone of occupation in Berlin.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Due to the rising tension in Europe and concerns over further Soviet expansion, American planners came up with a contingency plan code-named *Operation Dropshot* in 1949.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It considered possible nuclear and conventional war with the Soviet Union and its allies to counter a Soviet takeover of Western Europe, the Near East, and parts of Eastern Asia that they anticipated would begin around 1957.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In response, the United States. would saturate the Soviet Union with atomic and high-explosive bombs, and then invade and occupy the country.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The approach entailed a major buildup of U.S. nuclear forces and a corresponding reduction in America's non-nuclear ground and naval strength.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Greece, civil war broke out in 1946 between Anglo-American-supported royalist forces and communist-led forces, with the royalist forces emerging as the victors.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The U.S. launched a massive programme of military and economic aid to Greece and to neighbouring Turkey, arising from a fear that the Soviet Union stood on the verge of breaking through the NATO defence line to the oil-rich Middle East.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 12 March 1947, to gain Congressional support for the aid, President Truman described the aid as promoting democracy in defence of the "Free World," a principle that became known as the Truman Doctrine.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States sought to promote an economically strong and politically united Western Europe to counter the threat posed by the Soviet Union.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This was done openly using tools such as the European Recovery Program, which encouraged European economic integration.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The International Authority for the Ruhr, designed to keep German industry down and controlled, evolved into the European Coal and Steel Community (ECOSOC), a founding pillar of the European Union.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States also worked covertly to promote European integration, for example using the American Committee on United Europe to funnel funds to European federalist movements.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To ensure that Western Europe could withstand the Soviet military threat, the Western European Union was founded in 1948 and NATO in 1949.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The first NATO Secretary General, Lord Ismay, famously stated the organisation's goal was, "to keep the Russians out, the Americans in, and the Germans down." However without the manpower and industrial output of West Germany, no conventional defence of Western Europe had any hope of succeeding.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To remedy this, in 1950 the United States sought to promote the European Defence Community, which would have included a rearmed West Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The attempt was dashed when the French Parliament rejected it.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 9 May 1955, West Germany was instead admitted to NATO; the immediate result was the creation of the Warsaw Pact five days later.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Asia, the surrender of Japanese forces was complicated by the split between East and West as well as by the movement toward national self-determination in European colonial territories.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Decisions to decolonize British India led to an agreement to partition the country along religious lines into two independent dominions: India and Pakistan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The partition resulted in communal violence and massive displacements of the population.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It is often described as the largest mass human migration and one of the largest refugee crises in history.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As agreed to at the Yalta Conference, the Soviet Union declared war on Japan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Soviet forces invaded Manchuria which led to the collapse of the Manchukuo and expulsion of all Japanese settlers from the puppet state.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union dismantled the industrial base in Manchuria that the Japanese had built up and it subsequently became a base for the Communist Chinese forces due to the area being under Soviet occupation.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the end of the war, the Kuomintang (KMT) party (led by generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek) and the Communist Chinese forces resumed fighting each other, which they had temporarily suspended in order to fight Japan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The fight against the Japanese occupiers had strengthened popular support among the Chinese people for the Communist forces while it weakened the KMT, which depleted its strength fighting them.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Full-scale war between the KMT and CCF broke out in June 1946.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Despite United States' support for the Kuomintang, Communist forces ultimately prevailed and they established the People's Republic of China (PRC) on the mainland.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The KMT forces retreated to the island of Taiwan in 1949 where they established the Republic of China (ROC).
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] With the Communist victory in the civil war, the Soviet Union gave up its claim to military bases in China that were given to it by its Western Allies at the end of World War II.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] While large scale hostilities largely ceased by 1950, intermittent clashes occurred between the two from 1950 to 1979.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Taiwan unilaterally declared the civil war over in 1991, but no formal peace treaty or truce has been signed and the PRC continues to officially see Taiwan as a breakaway province that rightfully belongs to it.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The outbreak of the Korean War a few months after the conclusion of the Chinese Civil War and continued U.S. support for the KMT were the main reasons that prevented the PRC from invading Taiwan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the Yalta Conference, the Allies agreed that an undivided post-war Korea would be placed under 4-power multinational trusteeship.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] After Japan's surrender, this agreement was modified to a joint Soviet-American occupation of Korea.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The agreement was that Korea would be divided and occupied by the Soviets from the north and the Americans from the south.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Korea, formerly under Japanese rule, and which had been partially occupied by the Red Army following the Soviet Union's entry into the war against Japan, was divided at the 38th parallel on the orders of the U.S.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] A United States military government in southern Korea was established in the capital city of Seoul.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The US military commander, Lieutenant General John R.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Hodge, enlisted many former Japanese administrative officials to serve in this government.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] North of the military line, the Soviets administered the disarming and demobilisation of repatriated Korean nationalist guerrillas who had fought on the side of Chinese nationalists against the Japanese in Manchuria during World War II.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Simultaneously, the Soviets enabled a build-up of heavy armaments to pro-communist forces in the north.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The military line became a political line in 1948, when separate republics emerged on both sides of the 38th parallel, each republic claiming to be the legitimate government of Korea.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It culminated in the north invading the south, start of the Korean War two years later.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Labour and civil unrest broke out in the British colony of Malaya in 1946.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] A state of emergency was declared by the colonial authorities in 1948 with the outbreak of acts of terrorism.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The situation deteriorated into a full-scale anti-colonial insurgency, or Anti-British National Liberation War as the insurgents referred to it, led by the Malayan National Liberation Army (MNLA), the military wing of the Malayan Communist Party.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Malayan Emergency would endure for the next twelve years, ending in 1960.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1967, communist leader Chin Peng reopened hostilities, culminating in a second emergency that lasted until 1989.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Events after World War II in French Indochina, which consisted of the territories of modern-day Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia, set the stage for Indochina wars.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By 1941 during World War II, Japan gained full military access across Indochina and established a fragile dual colonial rule that maintained French administration while facilitating Japanese preparations for Southeast Asian operations.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The communist-controlled Viet Minh Front was formed in 1941 to fight against both Japanese and French forces.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Because the French colonial authorities began holding secret talks with Free France, the Japanese carried out a coup d’état on 9 March 1945.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] When Japan surrendered in August, this created a power vacuum, and the Viet Minh seized power during the August Revolution, declaring the independence of the Democratic Republic of Vietnam.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, the Allies (including the Soviet Union) all agreed that the area belonged to the French.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] From 1945 onward, the Vietnamese were locked in civil conflicts over the destiny of their post-colonial state after the ousting of the French and the surrender of Japan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Meanwhile, Nationalist Chinese forces moved in from the north and British from the south (as the French were unable to do so immediately themselves) and then handed power to the French, a process completed by March 1946.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Attempts to integrate the Democratic Republic of Vietnam with French rule failed and the Viet Minh launched their rebellion against the French rule starting the First Indochina War that same year (the Viet Minh organized common fronts to fight the French in Laos and Cambodia).
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The war ended in 1954 with the French withdrawal and the partition of Vietnam, which was intended to be temporary until elections could be held.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Democratic Republic of Vietnam controlled the North, while the State of Vietnam held the South.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Ngo Dinh Diem, backed by the United States in his refusal to hold elections, which he claimed would be unfair due to communist rigging, established the Republic of Vietnam.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Communist insurgents in the South formed the NLF under the direct guidance of North Vietnam to fight against the South Vietnamese government, a conflict that ultimately ended with North Vietnam conquering the South in April 1975.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Japan invaded and occupied the Dutch East Indies during the war and replaced the colonial government with a new administration.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Although the top positions were held by Japanese officers, the internment of all Dutch citizens meant that Indonesians filled many leadership and administrative positions.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the Japanese surrender in August 1945, Indonesian nationalist leaders such as Sukarno and Mohammad Hatta declared Indonesia as independent.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] A four-and-a-half-year struggle followed as the Dutch tried to re-establish their rule in colony, using a significant portion of their Marshall Plan aid to this end.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Dutch were aided by British forces for the first phase of the conflict until the United Kingdom withdrew.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The British also initially used 35,000 Japanese Surrendered Personnel to support their military operations in Indonesia.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Although Dutch forces re-occupied most of Indonesia, an Indonesian guerrilla campaign supported by the majority of Indonesians ensured, and ultimately international opinion favoured independence.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In December 1949, the Netherlands formally recognised Indonesian sovereignty.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] British covert operations in the Baltic States, which began in 1944 against the Nazis, escalated following the war.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In Operation Jungle, the Secret Intelligence Service (known as MI6) recruited and trained Estonians, Latvians, and Lithuanians for the clandestine work in the Baltic states between 1948 and 1955.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Leaders of the operation included Alfons Rebane, Stasys Žymantas, and Rūdolfs Silarājs.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The agents were transported under the cover of the "British Baltic Fishery Protection Service." They launched from British-occupied Germany, using a converted World War II E-boat captained and crewed by former members of the wartime German navy.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] British intelligence also trained and infiltrated anti-communist agents into Soviet Union from across the Finnish border, with orders to assassinate Soviet officials.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In the end, counter-intelligence supplied to the KGB by Kim Philby allowed the KGB to penetrate and ultimately gain control of MI6's entire intelligence network in the Baltic states.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Vietnam and the Middle East would later damage the reputation gained by the U.S. during its successes in Europe.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The KGB believed that the Third World rather than Europe was the arena in which it could win the Cold War.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Moscow would in later years fuel an arms buildup in Africa.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In later years, African countries used as proxies in the Cold War would often become "failed states" of their own.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] When the divisions of postwar Europe began to emerge, the war crimes programmes and denazification policies of Britain and the United States were relaxed in favour of recruiting German scientists, especially nuclear and long-range rocket scientists.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Many of these, prior to their capture, had worked on developing the German V-2 long-range rocket at the Baltic coast German Army Research Center Peenemünde.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In Operation Paperclip, beginning in 1945, the United States imported 1,600 German scientists and technicians as part of the intellectual reparations owed to the US and the UK, including about $10 billion (US$165 billion in 2025 dollars) in patents and industrial processes.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The wartime activities of some Operation Paperclip scientists would later be investigated.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Arthur Rudolph left the United States in 1984 in order to not be prosecuted.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Similarly, Georg Rickhey, who came to the United States under Operation Paperclip in 1946, was returned to Germany to stand trial at the Mittelbau-Dora war crimes trial in 1947.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Following his acquittal, he returned to the United States in 1948 and eventually became a U.S. citizen.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviets began Operation Osoaviakhim in 1946.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] NKVD and Soviet army units effectively deported thousands of military-related technical specialists from the Soviet occupation zone of post-war Germany to the Soviet Union.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviets used 92 trains to transport the specialists and their families, an estimated 10,000 to 15,000 people.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Much related equipment was also moved, the aim being to virtually transplant research and production centres, such as the relocated V-2 rocket centre at Mittelwerk Nordhausen, from Germany to the Soviet Union.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Among the people moved were Helmut Gröttrup and about two hundred scientists and technicians from Mittelwerk.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Personnel were also taken from AEG, BMW's Stassfurt jet propulsion group, IG Farben's Leuna chemical works, Junkers, Schott AG, Siebel, Telefunken, and Carl Zeiss AG.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The operation was commanded by NKVD deputy Colonel General Serov, outside the control of the local Soviet Military Administration.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The major reason for the operation was the Soviet fear of being condemned for noncompliance with Allied Control Council agreements on the liquidation of German military installations.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Some Western observers thought Operation Osoaviakhim was a retaliation for the failure of the Socialist Unity Party in elections, though Osoaviakhim was clearly planned before that.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As a general consequence of the war and in an effort to maintain international peace, the Allies formed the United Nations, which officially came into existence on 24 October 1945.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The United Nations replaced the defunct League of Nations as an intergovernmental organization.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The League was formally dissolved on 20 April 1946, but had in practice ceased to function in 1939, being unable to stop the outbreak of World War II.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The UN inherited some of the bodies of the League, such as the International Labour Organization.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] League of Nations mandate, mostly territories that had changed hands in World War I, became United Nations trust territories.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] South West Africa, an exception, was still governed under terms of the original mandate.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As the successor body to the League, the United Nations still assumed a supervisory role over the territory.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Free City of Danzig, a semi-autonomous city-state that was partly overseen by the League, became part of Poland.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The United Nations adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights in 1948, "as a common standard of achievement for all peoples and all nations." The Soviet Union abstained from voting on adoption of the declaration.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The U.S. did not ratify the social and economic rights sections.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The five major Allied powers were given permanent membership in the UN Security Council.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The permanent members can veto any Security Council resolution, the only UN decisions that are binding according to international law.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The five powers at the time of founding were: the United States, United Kingdom, France, Soviet Union, and Republic of China.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Republic of China lost the Chinese Civil War and retreated to the island of Taiwan by 1950 but continued to be a permanent member of the Council even though the *de facto* state in control of mainland China was the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] This was changed in 1971 when the PRC was given the permanent membership previously held by the Republic of China.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Russia inherited the permanent membership of the Soviet Union in 1991 after the dissolution of that state.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Japanese holdouts persisted on various islands in the Pacific Theatre until at least 1974.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Although all hostilities are now resolved, a peace treaty has never been signed between Japan and Russia due to the Kuril Islands dispute.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] By the end of the war, the European economy had collapsed with some 70% of its industrial infrastructure destroyed.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The property damage in the Soviet Union consisted of complete or partial destruction of 1,710 cities and towns, 70,000 villages/hamlets, and 31,850 industrial establishments.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The strength of the economic recovery following the war varied throughout the world, though in general, it was quite robust, particularly in the United States.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In Europe, West Germany, after having continued to decline economically during the first years of the Allied occupation, later experienced a remarkable recovery, and had by the end of the 1950s doubled production from its pre-war levels.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Italy came out of the war in poor economic condition, but by the 1950s, the Italian economy was marked by stability and high growth.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] France rebounded quickly and enjoyed rapid economic growth and modernisation under the Monnet Plan.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The United Kingdom, by contrast, was in a state of economic ruin after the war and continued to experience relative economic decline for decades to follow.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviet Union also experienced a rapid increase in production in the immediate post-war era.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Japan experienced rapid economic growth, becoming one of the most powerful economies in the world by the 1980s.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] China, following the conclusion of its civil war, was essentially bankrupt.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] By 1953, economic restoration seemed fairly successful as production had resumed pre-war levels.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Although China's growth rate mostly persisted, it was severely disrupted by the economic experiments of the Great Leap Forward, due to the resulting famine that caused the deaths of 15 to 55 million people.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] At the end of the war, the United States produced roughly half of the world's industrial output.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The United States, of course, had been spared industrial and civilian devastation.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Further, much of its pre-war industry had been converted to wartime usage.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As a result, with its industrial and civilian base in much better shape than most of the world, the United States embarked on an economic expansion unseen in human history.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] U.S. gross domestic product increased from $228 billion in 1945 to just under $1.7 trillion in 1975.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 1951 several laws were passed, ending the denazification.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As a result, many people with a former Nazi past ended up again in the political apparatus of West Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] West German President Walter Scheel and Chancellor Kurt Georg Kiesinger were both former members of the Nazi Party.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 1957, 77% of the West German Ministry of Justice's senior officials were former Nazi Party members.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Konrad Adenauer's State Secretary Hans Globke had played a major role in drafting antisemitic Nuremberg Race Laws in Nazi Germany.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The historical consensus is that West Germany's efforts at denazification proved wanting.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 2019, the then Germany’s President Frank-Walter Steinmeier has apologized, in Wieluń in Poland, on behalf of Germany, for the “German tyranny” in World War II over Poland.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Unexploded ordnance continues to pose a danger in the present day.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 2017, 50 thousand people were evacuated from Hanover so World War II era bombs could be defused.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As of 2023, it is still thought that thousands of unexploded bombs remain from World War II.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] When World War II ended, scientists did not have procedures for safe disposal of chemical arsenals.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] At the direction of the UK, US and Russia, chemical weapons were loaded onto ships by the metric ton and dumped into the sea.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The exact locations of the dumping are not known due to poor record keeping, but it is estimated that 1 million metric tons of chemical weapons remain on the ocean floor where they are rusting and pose the risk of leaks.
[src:consumer-organization/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Sulfur mustard exposure has been reported in some parts of coastal Italy and sulfur mustard bombs have been found as far as Delaware, likely brought in with the shellfish cargo.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] The **Alliance for Justice** (**AFJ**) is a progressive judicial advocacy group in the United States.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] Founded in 1979 by Nan Aron, AFJ monitors federal judicial appointments.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] AFJ represents a coalition of 135 politically liberal groups that have an interest in the federal judiciary.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] The Alliance for Justice presents a modern liberal viewpoint on legal issues.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] AFJ launched the Judicial Selection Project in 1985 to monitor the federal judicial appointment system.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] According to AFJ's founder, Nan Aron, the organization wanted to guard against the ideological impact of Ronald Reagan's federal judicial nominees.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] AFJ objects to judicial nominees who oppose abortion or who promise to exercise judicial restraint.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] The organization provides background on prospective nominees to the American Bar Association and the Senate Judiciary Committee.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] AFJ played a role in the defeat of Ronald Reagan nominee Robert Bork's nomination to the Supreme Court of the United States in 1987.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] In 2001, the organization supported the nomination of Roger Gregory, a Bill Clinton nominee and the first African-American judge in the Fourth Circuit in 2001.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] In 2013, AFJ supported President Barack Obama's three nominees for the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.
[src:consumer-organization/alliance-for-justice] AFJ reports a membership of over 130 organizations.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerism is concerned with the actions of individuals, as well as businesses where they act in pursuit of financial and economic goals at the expense of the perceived public good.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Commonly, anti-consumerism is connected with concern for environmental protection, anti-globalization, and animal-rights.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] *Post-consumerism*, the prioritization of well-being over material prosperity, is a related ideology.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerism originated from criticism of consumption, arguably starting with Thorstein Veblen, who, in the book *The Theory of the Leisure Class: An Economic Study of Institutions* (1899), suggested that consumerism dates from the cradle of civilization.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] The term *consumerism* also denotes economic policies associated with Keynesian economics, and the belief that the free choice of consumers should dictate the economic structure of a society (cf. producerism).
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Modern political anti-consumerism developed in the 2000s.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerism can be seen as an extension of postmodern society, supporting a "decentralized culture", rejecting a hegemonic cultural imperialism of globalisation and consumption, and responding to negative impacts of consumption on the environment.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Predictors of anti-consumerist attitudes and behaviors at an individual level include concerns about environmental pollution or disruption of ecological balance, a desire to live a simple life, and a belief that a search for happiness should come from internal factors.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] The diversion of libidinal energy toward the consumption of consumer products, he argues, results in an addictive cycle of consumption, leading to hyper-consumption, the exhaustion of desire, and the reign of symbolic misery.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Examples of anti-consumerist works include the book *No Logo* (2000) by Naomi Klein, and documentary films such as *The Corporation* (2003), by Mark Achbar and Jennifer Abbott, and *Surplus: Terrorized into Being Consumers* (2003), by Erik Gandini.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerist beliefs are in some cases connected with religious beliefs.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Islamic prophet Muhammad frequently endorsed simple living and anti-consumerism.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerist messages are often raised in protests, including in the broader context of environmentalism and anti-corporate activism.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] A notable anti-consumerist protest community is Reverend Billy and the Church of Stop Shopping.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In the context of protest art, Banksy, an influential British graffitist, painter, activist and filmmaker, has created satirical and provocative works about the consumerist society.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Examples include "Napalm", an attack on Walt Disney Pictures and McDonald's, and "Show Me the Monet", among many others.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In his 2004 book *Cut It Out*, Banksy writes, "You owe the companies nothing.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Less than nothing, you especially don't owe them any courtesy.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] They have re-arranged the world to put themselves in front of you.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Practicing anti-consumerism can mean voluntarily simplifying and minimizing one's lifestyle; this can be in efforts to exist more sustainably in a consumer culture.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] These lifestyle changes, which include choosing paper bags over plastic bags when shopping, are also in line with anti-corporate activism and green consumerism—both large contributors to the ethical market.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Degrowth, commoning and other movements aim to collectively address sustainability issues through practices and approaches that radically reduce consumption and replace consumer culture with new ethics and values.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] The modern development of anti-consumerism is closely tied to the global environmental crisis, particularly the urgency surrounding climate change.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] As the world faces environmental degradation and the depletion of natural resources, anti-consumerist movements have gained momentum.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] These movements advocate for reducing overconsumption, promoting conscious consumption, and addressing waste, especially the growing plastic problem.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] A key argument for these movements is the need for both personal and systemic changes.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Many activists, such as George Monbiot, emphasize that overconsumption is a root cause of global crises like climate change, biodiversity loss, and environmental degradation.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Efforts like upcycling and reducing plastic waste are part of broader campaigns aimed at creating sustainable consumption patterns.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Moreover, critics of unchecked consumerism argue that solving these issues requires more than individual action; it also necessitates economic restructuring to lessen dependence on constant consumer spending.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] One crucial aspect of this movement is the call for "voluntary simplicity," which advocates for reducing material needs to reduce environmental impact.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] This is reflected in policies from international bodies like the United Nations, which has highlighted the importance of sustainable consumption in its development goals.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] By embracing a mindset of reducing consumption, both individuals and institutions can significantly lower emissions and resource use, addressing environmental challenges more effectively than through green technologies alone.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerists believe advertising plays a huge role in human life by informing values and assumptions of the cultural system, deeming what is acceptable, and determining social standards.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] They declare that ads create a hyper-real world where commodities appear as the key to securing happiness.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerists cite studies that find that individuals believe their quality of life improves in relation to social values that lie outside the capability of the marketplace.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Therefore, advertising attempts to equate the social with the material by utilizing images and slogans to link commodities with the real sources of human happiness, such as meaningful relationships.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Ads are then a detriment to society because they tell consumers that accumulating more and more possessions will bring them closer to self-actualization, or the concept of a complete and secure being.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerists claim that in a consumerist society, advertisement images disempower and objectify the consumer.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] By stressing individual power, choice and desire, advertising falsely implies the control lies with the consumer.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Because anti-consumerists believe commodities supply only short-term gratification, they detract from a sustainably happy society.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Further, advertisers have resorted to new techniques of capturing attention, such as the increased speed of ads and product placements.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In this way, commercials infiltrate the consumerist society and become an inextricable part of the culture.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In a review of research on materialistic values and goals, Tim Kasser (2016) argues that the pursuit of material possessions can lead to short-term gratification at the expense of long-term well-being.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerists condemn advertising because it constructs a simulated world that offers fantastical escapism to consumers, rather than reflecting actual reality.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] They further argue that ads depict the interests and lifestyles of the elite as natural; cultivating a deep sense of inadequacy among viewers.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] They denounce the use of beautiful models because they glamorize the commodity beyond the reach of the average individual.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Supporters of anti-consumerism often accuse advertising of attention theft, i.e. they believe it unjustifiably invades public areas, thereby imposing itself on people who consider its presence unwanted.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] American graphic designer Sean Tejaratchi expresses his resentment of this "ad creep" in a 1999 issue of his clip art zine *Crap Hound*: "Advertising increasingly invades my environment instead of letting me come to it on my own terms when I need it...
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] The most powerful and well-funded methods of mass communication in history have been used to create a one-way, unending flow of shit into my life...
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] As a classical defence pertinent in this context, Austrian economic advocates focus on the entrepreneur, promoting a productive lifestyle rather than a materialistic one wherein the individual is defined by things and not their self.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Moreover, the Austrian School dictates that the determinative estimate of goods and services motivate the demand for these commodities in order for their prices to be influenced by consumers.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Others have often hinted towards rivalry amongst consumers, in that all parties, producer and consumer alike, behave in an entrepreneurial manner; The latter's market process interpretation is assumed to have provided the entrepreneurial role only to the producer.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] This was subject to heavy debate during the Interwar era, in what was known as the socialist-calculation debate.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] The status of the consumer has rarely been of any discussion in Austrian economics since.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] However, it has drawn attention to some limited degree in relation to production, with practitioners in the field having abused consumer rationality, as well as recognising their abstinence from market elucidation.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Despite its revised instances of state interventionism, adherence to the consumer theory remained abundant via the supply and demand model of Keynesianism.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Paul Samuelson stated that neoclassical synthesis should have been utilised towards the extent of fiscal and monetary interventions in order for economic stabilisation and maintaining full employment, albeit emphasising that the market economy cannot solely ensure full employment.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] These are often in similar bearing with the main fundamentals of NNE, a revised edition of Neoclassical synthesis.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Developments within consumption theory of the movement were published in specialized journals.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Most of the expenditures area was addressed by consumer choice adaptations within the markets field against Keynesianism.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Labour markets are often focused upon two features, opportunity cost of leisure as well as wage rate; When wage rate increases, it hints that labourers are willing to work more and it concludes with them entering the labour force.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Irrespective of the presumed incentivisation, the contrary is entirely possible, whereby workers work less and consume further leisure.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Because of these interrelations, it is reasonable to determine that wage rates and labour supply both relate positively, albeit negative for opportunity of leisure.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Nevertheless, the theory argues for gradual wage increase over time within a competitive labour market.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] This is viewed by some as an early feature of new classical theory, since it has some relation to the real business-cycle theory in technological innovation, whereby implementing automation is often similar with becoming reliant over technology for economic output.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Critics of anti-consumerism have accused anti-consumerists of opposing modernity or utilitarianism, arguing that it can lead to elitism, primarily among libertarian viewpoints, who argue that every person should decide their level of consumption independent of outside influence.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Right-wing critics see anti-consumerism as rooted in socialism.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Consumerism tends to be associated with capitalism, so modern socialists tend to be anti-consumerist, with anti-consumerism described as having become "left wing common sense".
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In 1999, the libertarian magazine *Reason* attacked anti-consumerism, claiming Marxist academics were repackaging themselves as anti-consumerists.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Twitchell, a professor at the University of Florida and popular writer, referred to anti-consumerist arguments as "Marxism Lite".
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] There have also been socialist critics of anti-consumerism who see it as a form of anti-modern "reactionary socialism", and state that anti-consumerism has also been adopted by ultra-conservatives and fascists.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Rather than being incompatible with left-wing political ideologies, it has been argued that "it is not the working class that needs to be liberated from consumerism, or in other words their own material desires, but that consumerism should be liberated from capitalism".
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In her book "Authenticity Guaranteed", Sally Robinson provides a feminist critique of anti-consumerism.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] She articulates that the stances of anti-consumerists reflect a hierarchical gendered framework which concerns preservation of masculinity in its purest form from the feminine social mechanisms of consumerism that curtails masculine agency and authenticity.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Citations of films such as *Fight Club* as an often anti-consumerist exemplary, according to her, presents consumerism as a crisis of masculinity in general.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] An anti-consumerist critique relies on the assumption that consumer culture is inauthentic and de-individualizing; therefore, it must also identify and delineate what constitutes the authentic and the individual.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In studies about whether anti-consumerism has been effective, it has been proven that for teenagers and young adults, the culture of media and their relationship often makes it difficult for them to reject consumerism.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] *Science Daily* has a report on this, and states that it is either because they have little independence to develop their own agenda, or because they are dependent on their own consumer activities (e.g. bars, clubs and shops) to retain some independent income.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In *Fight Club*, the protagonist finds himself participating in terroristic acts against corporate society and consumer culture.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] The film is regarded as one of the most widely recognizable pieces of anti-consumerist media.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] The success of the book and the film comes despite the author Chuck Palahniuk publicly stating that the story is both anticonsumerist and anticommercialist.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In the novel *American Psycho* by Bret Easton Ellis, the protagonist Patrick Bateman criticizes the consumerist society of America in the 1980s of which he is a personification.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] Later on he goes on a killing spree without any consequences, suggesting that the people around him are so self-absorbed and focused on consuming that they either do not see or do not care about his acts.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In the *Pixar* movie, *WALL-E*, Earth is depicted in an apocalyptic state caused by the negative effects of human consumerism.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] In the 2024 working paper *Anti-Consumerism: Stick or Carrot?* (by Iwan Bos et al.), an economic model compares the "stick" and "carrot" policies of anti-consumerism.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] The "stick" policy aims to impose psychic costs (e.g., guilt) on consumers; the "carrot" policy, conversely, provides psychic benefits (e.g., pride) to non-consumers.
[src:consumer-organization/anti-consumerism] The study found that while both approaches (weakly) reduce consumption and profits, the "carrot" policy "strictly outperforms" the "stick" policy in terms of social and consumer welfare.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The implication behind the use of the term is that instead of a "true" or "natural" grassroots effort behind the activity in question, there is a "fake" or "artificial" appearance of support.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] It is increasingly recognized as a problem in social media, e-commerce, and politics.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Astroturfing can influence public opinion by flooding platforms like political blogs, news sites, and review websites with manipulated content.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Some groups accused of astroturfing argue that they are legitimately helping citizen activists to make their voices heard.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Various detection methods have been developed by researchers, including content analysis, linguistic analysis, authorship attribution, and machine learning.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The word "grassroots" describes a natural, self-organizing movement run by the community.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] AstroTurf is a brand of artificial turf (grass); "astroturf" describes an artificial grassroots movement.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In political science, it is defined as the process of seeking electoral victory or legislative relief for grievances by helping political actors find and mobilize a sympathetic public, and is designed to create the image of public consensus where there is none.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Astroturfing is the use of fake grassroots efforts that primarily focus on influencing public opinion and typically are funded by corporations and political entities to form opinions.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] On the internet, "astroturfers" use software to hide their identity.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Sometimes one individual operates through many personas to give the impression of widespread support for their client's agenda.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Some studies suggest astroturfing can alter public viewpoints and create enough doubt to inhibit action.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In the first systematic study of astroturfing in the United States, Oxford Professor Philip N.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Howard argued that the internet was making it much easier for powerful lobbyists and political movements to activate small groups of aggrieved citizens to have an exaggerated importance in public policy debates.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Twitter trends are often targeted by astroturfing as they are used as a proxy for popularity.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] A study conducted by researchers at EPFL reported that 20% of the global Twitter trends in 2019 were fake, created automatically using fake and compromised accounts which tweet in a coordinated way to mimic grassroots organizing of regular Twitter users.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Many countries have laws that prohibit more overt astroturfing practices.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In the United States, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) may send cease-and-desist orders or require a fine of $16,000 per day for those that violate its "Guides Concerning the Use of Endorsements and Testimonials in Advertising".
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The FTC's guides were updated in 2009 to address social media and word-of-mouth marketing.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] According to an article in the *Journal of Consumer Policy*, the FTC's guides holds advertisers responsible for ensuring bloggers or product endorsers comply with the guides, and any product endorsers with a material connection are required to provide honest reviews.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In the European Union, the Unfair Commercial Practices Directive requires that paid-for editorial content in the media provide a clear disclosure that the content is a sponsored advertisement.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Additionally, it prohibits those with a material connection from misleading readers into thinking they are a regular consumer.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The United Kingdom has the Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations, which prohibits "Falsely representing oneself as a consumer." They allow for up to two years in prison and unlimited fines for breaches.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Additionally, the advertising industry in the UK has adopted many voluntary policies, such as the Code of Non-Broadcast Advertising, Sale, Promotion and Direct Marketing.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] A trade association, the Advertising Standards Authority, investigates complaints of breaches.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The policy requires that marketing professionals not mislead their audience, including by omitting a disclosure of their material connection.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In Australia, astroturfing is regulated by Section 18 of the Australian Consumer Law, which broadly prohibits "misleading and deceptive conduct".
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] According to the *Journal of Consumer Policy*, Australia's laws, which were introduced in 1975, are more vague.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In most cases, they are enforced through lawsuits from competitors, rather than the regulatory body, the Australian Competition & Consumer Commission.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] There is also an International Consumer Protection and Enforcement Network (ICPEN).
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Legal regulations are primarily targeted towards testimonials, endorsements and statements as to the performance or quality of a product.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Employees of an organization may be considered acting as customers if their actions are not guided by authority within the company.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Walker highlights the case of Working Families for Wal-Mart, in which the campaign's lack of transparency led to its demise.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] A study published in the *Journal of Business Ethics* examined the effects of websites operated by front groups on students.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] It found that astroturfing was effective at creating uncertainty and lowering trust about claims, thereby changing perceptions that tend to favor the business interests behind the astroturfing effort.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Online comments from astroturfing employees can also sway the discussion through the influence of groupthink.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Some astroturfing operatives defend their practice.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Regarding "movements that have organized aggressively to exaggerate their sway", author Ryan Sager said that this "isn't cheating.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Groups like FreedomWorks and Americans for Prosperity assert that providing organizational structure and support to grassroots movements is essential for effective advocacy.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] They argue that the concept of grassroots movements being entirely spontaneous is unrealistic and that some level of organization is necessary to amplify voices and mobilize supporters effectively.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] These groups claim that their activities are legitimate and that they are simply providing the necessary backbone for authentic activism.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Data-mining expert Bing Liu (University of Illinois Chicago) estimated that one-third of all consumer reviews on the Internet are fake.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] According to *The New York Times*, this has made it hard to tell the difference between "popular sentiment" and "manufactured public opinion".
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] According to an article in the *Journal of Business Ethics*, astroturfing threatens the legitimacy of genuine grassroots movements.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] George Monbiot said that persona-management software supporting astroturfing "could destroy the Internet as a forum for constructive debate".
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] An article in the *Journal of Consumer Policy* said that regulators and policy makers needed to be more aggressive about astroturfing.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The author said that it undermines the public's ability to inform potential customers of sub-standard products or inappropriate business practices, but also noted that fake reviews were difficult to detect.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Use of one or more front groups is one astroturfing technique.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] These groups typically present themselves as serving the public interest, while actually working on behalf of a corporate or political sponsor.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Front groups may resist legislation and scientific consensus that is damaging to the sponsor's business by emphasizing minority viewpoints, instilling doubt and publishing counterclaims by corporate-sponsored experts.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Fake blogs can also be created that appear to be written by consumers, while actually being operated by a commercial or political interest.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Some political movements have provided incentives for members of the public to send a letter to the editor at their local paper, often using a copy and paste form letter that is published in dozens of newspapers verbatim.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Mass letters may be printed on personalized stationery using different typefaces, colors and words to make them appear personal.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Another technique is the use of sockpuppets, where a single person creates multiple identities online to give the appearance of grassroots support.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Sockpuppets may post positive reviews about a product, attack participants that criticize the organization, or post negative reviews and comments about competitors, under fake identities.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Astroturfing businesses may pay staff based on the number of posts they make that are not flagged by moderators.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Persona management software may be used so that each paid poster can manage five to seventy convincing online personas without getting them confused.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Online astroturfing using sockpuppets is a form of Sybil attack against distributed systems.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Pharmaceutical companies may sponsor patient support groups and simultaneously push them to help market their products.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Bloggers who receive free products, paid travel or other accommodations may also be considered astroturfing if those gifts are not disclosed to the reader.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Analysts could be considered astroturfing, since they often cover their own clients without disclosing their financial connection.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] To avoid astroturfing, many organizations and press have policies about gifts, accommodations and disclosures.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Persona management software can age accounts and simulate the activity of attending a conference automatically to make it more convincing that they are genuine.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] At HBGary, employees were given separate thumb drives that contain online accounts for individual identities and visual cues to remind the employee which identity they are using at the time.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] According to an article in *The New York Times*, the Federal Trade Commission rarely enforces its astroturfing laws.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Operations are frequently detected if their profile images are recognized or if they are identified through the usage patterns of their accounts.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Filippo Menczer's group at Indiana University developed software in 2010 that detects astroturfing on Twitter by recognizing behavioral patterns.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Researchers are exploring other techniques of detecting astroturfing including machine learning, linguistic analysis, and content analysis.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] According to an article in the *Journal of Consumer Policy*, academics disagree on how prolific astroturfing is.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] According to Nancy Clark from Precision Communications, grass-roots specialists charge $25 to $75 for each constituent they convince to send a letter to a politician.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Paid online commentators in China are purportedly paid 50 cents for each online post that is not removed by moderators, leading to the nickname of the "50-cent party".
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] *The New York Times* reported that a business selling fake online book reviews charged $999 for 50 reviews and made $28,000 a month shortly after opening.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] According to the *Financial Times*, astroturfing is "commonplace" in American politics, but was "revolutionary" in Europe when it was exposed that the European Privacy Association, an anti-privacy "think-tank", was actually sponsored by technology companies.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Although the term "astroturfing" was not yet developed, an early example of the practice was in Act 1, Scene 2 of Shakespeare's play *Julius Caesar*.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In the play, Gaius Cassius Longinus writes fake letters from "the public" to convince Brutus to assassinate Julius Caesar.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Patient advocacy groups funded by biopharmaceutical companies are common.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 1997, Schering Plough paid a P/R firm Schandwick International, to create a national coalition of patient advocacy groups promoting Schering's Rebotron, a treatment for Hepatitis C.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The groups pushed increased testing as a way to manufacture cases and lobbied state legislatures to cover the $18,000 treatment.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The groups also hosted telephone "information lines" with scripts written by the drug company and distributed "patient information" pamphlets promoting drug therapies over other alternatives and overstating the danger of the medical condition.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Manufacturers of AIDS drugs commonly fund LGBTQ organizations, which in turn, lobby to advance policies that increase AIDS drug sales.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2019, the communications director of AIDS United, a Washington DC–based coalition of AIDS service organizations, resigned, stating such funding creates conflicts of interest among gay rights activists.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In response to the passage of tobacco control legislation in the US, Philip Morris, Burson-Marsteller and other tobacco interests created the National Smokers Alliance (NSA) in 1993.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The NSA and other tobacco interests initiated an aggressive public relations campaign from 1994 to 1999 in an effort to exaggerate the appearance of grassroots support for smoker's rights.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] According to an article in the *Journal of Health Communication*, the NSA had mixed success at defeating bills that were damaging revenues of tobacco interests.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Email, automated phone calls, form letters, and the Internet made astroturfing more economical and prolific in the late 1990s.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The internet in particular has made astroturfing cheaper, more widespread, and harder to detect.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2001, as Microsoft was defending itself against an antitrust lawsuit, Americans for Technology Leadership (ATL), a group heavily funded by Microsoft, initiated a letter-writing campaign.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] ATL contacted constituents under the guise of conducting a poll and sent pro-Microsoft consumers form and sample letters to send to involved lawmakers.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The effort was designed to make it appear as though there was public support for a sympathetic ruling in the antitrust lawsuit.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In January 2018, YouTube user Isaac Protiva uploaded a video alleging that internet service provider Fidelity Communications was behind an initiative called "Stop City-Funded Internet", based on how some images on the Stop City-Funded Internet website had "Fidelity" in their file names.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The campaign appeared to be in response to the city of West Plains expanding its broadband network, and advocated for the end of municipal broadband on the basis that it was too risky.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Days later, Fidelity released a letter admitting to sponsoring the campaign.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2009–2010, an Indiana University research study developed a software system to detect astroturfing on Twitter due to the sensitivity of the topic in the run up to the 2010 U.S. midterm elections and account suspensions on the social media platform.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The study cited a limited number of examples, all promoting conservative policies and candidates.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2003, GOPTeamLeader.com offered the site's users "points" that could be redeemed for products if they signed a form letter promoting George Bush and got a local paper to publish it as a letter to the editor.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] More than 100 newspapers published an identical letter to the editor from the site with different signatures on it.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Similar campaigns were used by GeorgeWBush.com, and by MoveOn.org to promote Michael Moore's film *Fahrenheit 9/11*.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget's "Fix the Debt" campaign advocated to reduce government debt without disclosing that its members were lobbyists or high-ranking employees at corporations that aim to reduce federal spending.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] It also sent op-eds to various students that were published as-is.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Some organizations in the Tea Party movement have been accused of being astroturfed.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Its ads on Facebook used socialist memes and slogans to attack Democrats and urge third-party protest voting in several tight races, including the 2018 Wisconsin gubernatorial election.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2018, a website called "Jexodus" claiming to be by "proud Jewish Millennials tired of living in bondage to leftist politics" was set up by Jeff Ballabon, a Republican operative in his mid-50s.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The website was denounced as "likely a clumsy astroturf effort rather than an actual grassroots movement".
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The website was registered November 5, 2018, before the congressional election, and before those representatives accused of antisemitism had even been voted in.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] This website was later cited by Donald Trump as though it were an authentic movement.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] As of 2025, Jexodus was rebranded as “The Exodus Movement” and is no longer active.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] 1,586 spam replies were made over the course of fourteen days, until Twitter detected and suspended all of the bot accounts.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Astroturfing organizations have been used by the fossil fuel industry in their fight against climate action or to propagate climate change denial.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] These organizations typically use euphemistic names to disguise their sponsors and agendas and often target "green" organizations with which they can be confused.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Examples for such fossil fuel funded Astroturfing organizations are the National Wetlands Coalition, the Global Climate Coalition, the Greening Earth Society, the Washington Consumers for Sound Fuel Policy or the American Coalition for Clean Coal Energy.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Corporate efforts to mobilize the public against environmental regulation accelerated in the US following the election of president Barack Obama.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2014, the *Toronto Sun*, a conservative media organization, published an article accusing Russia of using astroturf tactics to drum up anti-fracking sentiment across Europe and the West, supposedly in order to maintain dominance in oil exports through Ukraine.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Fossil fuel company Glencore enlisted the C|T Group to conduct a coordinated pro-coal campaign called "Project Caesar" from 2017 onwards.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Drawing on an annual budget of between £4-7 million, it created what appeared to be grassroots social media pages and groups to promote anti-renewable messages.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2006, two Edelman employees created a blog called "Wal-Marting Across America" about two people traveling to Wal-Marts across the country.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The blog gave the appearance of being operated by spontaneous consumers, but was actually operated on behalf of Working Families for Walmart, a group funded by Wal-Mart.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2007, Ask.com deployed an anti-Google advertising campaign portraying Google as an "information monopoly" that was damaging the Internet.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The ad was designed to give the appearance of a popular movement and did not disclose it was funded by a competitor.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2010, the Federal Trade Commission settled a complaint with Reverb Communications, who was using interns to post favorable product reviews in Apple's iTunes store for clients.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In September 2012, one of the first major identified cases of astroturfing in Finland involved criticisms about the cost of a €1.8 billion patient information system, which was defended by fake online identities operated by involved vendors.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In September 2013, New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman announced a settlement with 19 companies to prevent astroturfing.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] "'Astroturfing' is the 21st century's version of false advertising, and prosecutors have many tools at their disposal to put an end to it," said Scheiderman.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The companies paid $350,000 to settle the matter, but the settlement opened the way for private suits as well.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] "Every state has some version of the statutes New York used," according to lawyer Kelly H.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] When the company's local PR manager was confronted about it, she deflected the questions and defended their intent.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The Southern Poverty Law Center has categorized Moms For Liberty as an extremist “reactionary” and "conservative populist" organization.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Founded on January 21, 2021, Moms For Liberty is a 501(c)(4) “social welfare” nonprofit.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The group has ties to far-right conservative figures, politicians, and groups, most notably, Florida governor Ron DeSantis and The Proud Boys.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2023, DeSantis appointed Moms For Liberty founder Tina Descovich to the Florida State Commission on Ethics.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Critics have derided the group's perceived meteoritic rise to fame as evidence of astroturfing.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] GLAAD notes that only one month after the group's formation, despite advertising themselves as a grassroots movement, garnered significant media attention from right wing circles.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] On January 27, 2021, the group was featured on the Rush Limbaugh show and was covered by far-right news publication Breitbart the following month.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Bridget Ziegler, one of the group's three founders, is also married to Christian Ziegler, the chair of the Florida GOP.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The National Organization for Marriage (NOM) is a nonprofit organization “with a mission to protect marriage”.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The group was formed in 2007 for the sole purpose of supporting California's Proposition 8, a state ballot measure to prohibit same-sex marriage, and continued to run similar campaigns in Massachusetts, Maine, and Oregon.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In 2008, Chinese affairs expert Rebecca MacKinnon estimated the Chinese government employed 280,000 people in a government-sponsored astroturfing operation to post pro-government propaganda on social media and drown out voices of dissent.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In June 2010, the United States Air Force solicited for "persona management" software that would "enable an operator to exercise a number of different online persons from the same workstation and without fear of being discovered by sophisticated adversaries.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The contract is thought to have been awarded as part of a program called Operation Earnest Voice, which was first developed as a psychological warfare weapon against the online presence of groups ranged against coalition forces.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] In August 2020, the US-based public relations firm CLS Strategies was linked to a network of accounts removed by Facebook due to violations of their policies in regards to foreign interference.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] 55 Facebook accounts, 42 pages, and 36 Instagram accounts were removed.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The information Facebook shared with investigators showed that the accounts focused on Venezuela, Bolivia, and Mexico, and included duplicate and fake accounts.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Records showed connections with CLS Strategies employees, and that some of the work appeared to be at the behest of the Bolivian Government.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Facebook had announced the closure of the accounts, stating that they targeted politics in the region and that $3.6 million was spent on advertising in the three countries on what they determined to be disinformation.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] CLS Strategies claimed the accusations made by Facebook were inaccurate.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] On April 11, 2022, seven weeks into the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, BBC published the results of investigation of a network of Facebook groups with the overall aim to promote the Russian president Vladimir Putin as a hero standing up to the West with overwhelming international support.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Members, activities, and interrelations in 10 pro-Putin public groups with more than 650,000 members between them in the time of writing, boasting names such as *Vladimir Putin - Leader of the Free World*, were analyzed.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Over a month, researchers counted 16,500 posts, receiving more than 3.6 million interactions.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] The campaign "creates the appearance of widespread support for Putin and the Kremlin in the shadow of the invasion and relies on... inauthentic accounts to accomplish its goal", according to a report.
[src:consumer-organization/astroturfing] Lead researcher Moustafa Ayad described the network and its practice of using tens of duplicate accounts in potential violation of Facebook's rules on inauthentic behavior as an example of *astroturfing*.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] Consumer Organizations may operate via protests, litigation, campaigning, or lobbying.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] They may engage in single-issue advocacy (e.g., the British Campaign for Real Ale (CAMRA), which campaigned against keg beer and for cask ale) or they may set themselves up as more general consumer watchdogs, such as the Consumers' Association in the UK.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] One common means of providing consumers useful information is the independent comparative survey or test of products or services, involving different manufacturers or companies (e.g., *Which?*, *Consumer Reports*, etc.).
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] Another arena where consumer organizations have operated is food safety.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] The needs for campaigning in this area are less easy to reconcile with their traditional methods, since the scientific, dietary or medical evidence is normally more complex than in other arenas, such as the electric safety of white goods.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] The current standards on mandatory labelling, in developed countries, have in part been shaped by past lobbying by consumer groups.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] The aim of consumer organizations may be to establish and to attempt to enforce consumer rights.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] Effective work has also been done, however, simply by using the threat of bad publicity to keep companies' focus on the consumers' point of view.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] Two precursor organizations to the modern consumer organization are standards organizations and consumers leagues.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] Both of these appeared in the United States around 1900.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] Trade associations and professional societies began to establish standards organizations to reduce industry waste and increase productivity.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] Consumer leagues modeled themselves after trade unions in their attempts to improve the market with boycotts in the same way that trade unions sought to improve working conditions with strike action.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] Aside from this general consumer organisation, the Netherlands is home to many categorical consumer organisations whose working terrain is limited to a certain part of the markets.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] In the United Kingdom, the Enterprise Act 2002 allows consumer bodies that have been approved by the Secretary of State for Trade and Industry to be designated as "super-complainants" to the Competition and Markets Authority.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] By 1969 most capitalist countries with developed marketplaces hosted consumer organizations that published consumer magazines which reported the results of product testing.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] Internationally, the idea of consumer organizations spread from Consumers Union in the United States starting in 1956.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] The growth of interest in product testing journalism might be explained by increased consumption of mass-marketed products in and before that period.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] That increased international consumption itself was an effect of the aftermath of World War II.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] In the 25 years after World War II, there was a correlation between the number of people in a country who were purchasing cars and the popularity of consumer magazines.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] In some cases, an increase in other consumer purchases seemed to drive popularity of consumer magazines, but the correlation was closest for populations who made decisions about buying cars.
[src:consumer-organization/consumer-organization] The availability of consumer magazines comforted consumers when individuals in society suddenly became overwhelmed with marketplace decisions, and the popularity of magazines seemed to grow as more marketplace decisions became available.
